00:17:56.570 --> 00:17:59.310
of how science works
and why we think

00:17:59.310 --> 00:18:02.720
about the origins of
life the way we do.

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:06.390
I open with one of my
favorite illustrations

00:18:06.390 --> 00:18:09.960
by M.C. Escher, Three Worlds.

00:18:09.960 --> 00:18:14.460
In one sense this is all
one world, of course, right?

00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:18.460
Yet the tree and the carp
are unaware of each other.

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:21.980
The pond surface, the
interface between the two,

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:25.990
reflects one and reveals the other.

00:18:25.990 --> 00:18:28.620
In the world of the
picture it constructs both.

00:18:28.620 --> 00:18:32.740
Well, I want to do something
similar to that with one

00:18:32.740 --> 00:18:40.550
of the central concepts in origin
of life research, the RNA world.

00:18:40.550 --> 00:18:44.640
The usual explanation of what
the RNA world is goes something

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:46.490
like this.

00:18:46.490 --> 00:18:50.010
There's a chicken-and-egg problem
at the heart of modern biology.

00:18:50.010 --> 00:18:55.800
Most of the genes spelled out in
our DNA encode the instructions

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:57.760
for making proteins.

00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:02.130
Among the most important proteins
are enzymes, complex molecules

00:19:02.130 --> 00:19:04.810
that catalyze biological reactions.

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:11.980
Among the reactions that enzymes
catalyze are the synthesis of DNA.

00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:14.330
In other words, you can't
make proteins without genes

00:19:14.330 --> 00:19:16.300
and you can't make
genes without proteins.

00:19:16.300 --> 00:19:20.280
How did this system evolve?

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:23.040
The RNA world breaks
this infinite loop.

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:28.590 position:56%
Differing from DNA by only one atom
it's capable of storing information,

00:19:28.590 --> 00:19:31.820
just like DNA, but it's
usually single stranded,

00:19:31.820 --> 00:19:34.570
which means it's more
chemically reactive than DNA.

00:19:34.570 --> 00:19:41.630 position:56%
In fact, in the 1980s researchers
found that RNA can act as an enzyme.

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:46.570
It can then in theory copy itself,

00:19:46.570 --> 00:19:50.800
perhaps it also evolved
a way to make proteins.

00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:54.990
So proof there goes the
chicken-and-egg problem

00:19:54.990 --> 00:19:59.350
and a bird-like dinosaur
gave rise to both, all right?

00:19:59.350 --> 00:20:01.350
That's the RNA world.

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:06.180
So the RNA world then
describes a time very early

00:20:06.180 --> 00:20:13.540
in evolution before DNA, before
protein, when RNA did both jobs.

00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:19.150 position:56%
Eventually it handed off information
storage to DNA, which is more stable

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:24.930
and can copy itself very easily,
and it handed off most catalysis

00:20:24.930 --> 00:20:29.030
to proteins, which are more
complex and versatile and,

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:31.330
therefore, more powerful.

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:38.220
The canonical history of the
RNA world is very simple.

00:20:38.220 --> 00:20:42.990
In the 1960s the researchers
first speculated

00:20:42.990 --> 00:20:46.260
on the idea of RNA catalysis.

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:51.480 position:56%
The first person always mentioned
is Francis Crick of Watson and Crick

00:20:51.480 --> 00:20:56.790
and the double helix, and often
usually mentioned is his colleague,

00:20:56.790 --> 00:20:58.090
Leslie Orgel.

00:20:58.090 --> 00:21:01.480
Sometimes the renegade
Microbiologist,

00:21:01.480 --> 00:21:04.390
Carl Woese, is also mentioned.

00:21:04.390 --> 00:21:08.370
Then people say there was a
period in which not much was done

00:21:08.370 --> 00:21:12.500
with this idea because it was just
a speculation and no one knew what

00:21:12.500 --> 00:21:18.230
to do with it until in the early
'80s RNA catalysis was actually

00:21:18.230 --> 00:21:26.570
found twice by Tom Cech's group
at Colorado and then independently

00:21:26.570 --> 00:21:29.070
by Sidney Altman's [Assumed
Spelling] group at Yale.

00:21:29.070 --> 00:21:34.270
And then shortly thereafter
the RNA world was articulated

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:38.210
by Walter Gilbert in 1986.

00:21:38.210 --> 00:21:41.770
And that's sort of it.

00:21:41.770 --> 00:21:46.000 position:56%
Well, surprise, surprise, I've found

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.900
that there's a lot
more to it than that.

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:52.960
There is a rich context and
an earlier history going back

00:21:52.960 --> 00:21:57.030
to the early 1950s that I
can only weigh that today.

00:21:57.030 --> 00:22:01.780
I'm going to spend most of my
time cutting into this period

00:22:01.780 --> 00:22:05.930
in which supposedly nothing
happened and I'm going to close

00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:12.090
with a few remarks on how this
narrative of the RNA world

00:22:12.090 --> 00:22:18.310
that people understand was carved
out of all of this other stuff

00:22:18.310 --> 00:22:19.610
that I'm going to be talking about.

00:22:19.610 --> 00:22:23.540
My hope is to give you at least a
taste of what was really at stake

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:27.040
in the creation of the RNA world.

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:31.610
So here briefly are the remarks
that earned the early guys' credit

00:22:31.610 --> 00:22:33.920
for predicting the RNA world.

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:40.980
In his 1967 book, The
Genetic Code, Carl Woese wrote

00:22:40.980 --> 00:22:43.910
of the era of nucleic acid life.

00:22:43.910 --> 00:22:48.070
This was based on a speculative
and later disproven idea

00:22:48.070 --> 00:22:51.890
about the function of the
molecule transfer RNA,

00:22:51.890 --> 00:22:54.920
and in this Woese concluded

00:22:54.920 --> 00:23:00.430
that a proto RNA could have
been the original genome.

00:23:00.430 --> 00:23:03.470
Then the next year
Francis Crick imagined

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:09.150 position:56%
that the primitive protein synthesis
machinery could have been made

00:23:09.150 --> 00:23:12.150
entirely of RNA.

00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:17.520 position:56%
In a companion paper in the same
journal his colleague, Leslie Orgel,

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:22.600
said that a primordial protein
only world was impossible

00:23:22.600 --> 00:23:26.610
because of the nature of
proteins they're not able

00:23:26.610 --> 00:23:30.430
to template their own replication

00:23:30.430 --> 00:23:35.660
and a nucleic acid only
world was possible,

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:38.550
but he said it wouldn't
have gotten very far,

00:23:38.550 --> 00:23:43.080
it wouldn't have gotten past
what he called the stage

00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:49.070
of evolutionary doodling until
it had evolved a genetic code

00:23:49.070 --> 00:23:55.500
to link nucleic acids
and proteins, okay?

00:23:55.500 --> 00:24:03.220 position:56%
So my main point here is simply that
because the early RNA world evolved

00:24:03.220 --> 00:24:04.920
around the genetic code

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:09.380
and its origin it presumed
the existence of protein.

00:24:09.380 --> 00:24:12.480
That's not true for
the later RNA world.

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:18.680
So thinking about the genetic
code implies an RNA protein world.

00:24:18.680 --> 00:24:24.140
Because today is - oh, and
here's the RNA protein world,

00:24:24.140 --> 00:24:25.940
this is the genetic code.

00:24:25.940 --> 00:24:30.670
And so even from these
brief snippets it's obvious

00:24:30.670 --> 00:24:33.590
that all these three were
writing in the context

00:24:33.590 --> 00:24:35.310
of making proteins, right?

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:38.080
The genetic code and
the nucleotide sequence

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:44.310
of the transfer RNA had just been
solved in the preceding years,

00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:47.960
in the 1960s, crowning
touches on a decade's worth

00:24:47.960 --> 00:24:52.100
of spectacular research
characterizing the machinery

00:24:52.100 --> 00:24:55.750
involved in reading out
the nucleic acid sequence

00:24:55.750 --> 00:24:59.020
and converting it into proteins.

00:24:59.020 --> 00:25:02.670
And the whole complicated
process was shot through with RNA.

00:25:02.670 --> 00:25:08.790
We had messenger RNA,
transfer RNA, ribosomal RNA.

00:25:08.790 --> 00:25:15.510
And so molecular biologists saw
the flow of genetic information

00:25:15.510 --> 00:25:20.350
through the cell as one of
the defining essences of life

00:25:20.350 --> 00:25:25.720
and this essence was
mediated by RNA.

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:27.020
Even though they weren't trained

00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:30.230
in evolutionary biology they
immediately recognized the question

00:25:30.230 --> 00:25:33.160
of how something is
abstract and self-referential

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:37.080
as the genetic code could
have evolved and that

00:25:37.080 --> 00:25:39.460
that was a knotty and
important problem.

00:25:39.460 --> 00:25:42.970
So this is the RNA protein world.

00:25:42.970 --> 00:25:46.440
Now because my focus today is
mainly on Walter Gilbert I'm going

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:49.730 position:56%
to jump forward a few years to 1976.

00:25:49.730 --> 00:25:52.680
That year Gilbert and
his student, Allan Maxam,

00:25:52.680 --> 00:25:57.000
invented a new technique
for sequencing DNA.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:02.530
The paper describing the method
was published in February of 1977.

00:26:02.530 --> 00:26:08.200
This followed the method invented
by Frederick Sanger in 1975,

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:11.700
but Maxam-Gilbert sequencing
was a good deal faster

00:26:11.700 --> 00:26:15.230
and it became the method of
choice for sequencing DNA

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:19.070
until automated DNA
sequencing came in in the 1990s,

00:26:19.070 --> 00:26:23.650
which sort of sent us hurtling
toward the human genome project.

00:26:23.650 --> 00:26:26.930
Gilbert had trained as a
physicist, but had been immersed

00:26:26.930 --> 00:26:31.040
in the RNA world since
the mid-1950s.

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:36.250
He had participated in the
discovery of messenger RNA in 1960

00:26:36.250 --> 00:26:40.510
and he shared the laboratory
of Jim Watson, the other half

00:26:40.510 --> 00:26:42.710
of Watson and Crick at Harvard.

00:26:42.710 --> 00:26:48.320
And in 1976 Watson moved
down to Long Island

00:26:48.320 --> 00:26:51.890
to become fulltime Director of
Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory

00:26:51.890 --> 00:26:55.440
and bequeathed his
entire lab to Gilbert,

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:58.080
and Gilbert did some pretty
interesting things there.

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:04.520
So in the spring of 1977 the
immunologist, Susumu Tonegawa,

00:27:04.520 --> 00:27:11.250
visited Gilbert's lab and in order
to sequence some of the genes

00:27:11.250 --> 00:27:16.780 position:56%
that he was finding for
immunoglobulins, important molecules

00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:20.590
that create the antigens
that recognize the antibodies

00:27:20.590 --> 00:27:22.270
in our immune system, okay?

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:26.650
And Gilbert says when
he says Tonegawa came

00:27:26.650 --> 00:27:29.850
to sequence it he meant
that Maxam sequenced it.

00:27:29.850 --> 00:27:37.260
And Maxam found when he was doing
this, found this 93 base sequence

00:27:37.260 --> 00:27:41.510
that appeared to be skipped
over during transcription.

00:27:41.510 --> 00:27:48.170
So the messenger RNA from the
gene was missing this chunk

00:27:48.170 --> 00:27:50.270
of DNA, right?

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:54.350
And they didn't quite
know what to do with that,

00:27:54.350 --> 00:28:00.610
but that June they went down to
Long Island to the Annual Symposium

00:28:00.610 --> 00:28:03.050
at Cold Spring Harbor
Lab where they heard

00:28:03.050 --> 00:28:05.650
about a stunning new
development in gene structure

00:28:05.650 --> 00:28:08.600
in higher organisms or eukaryotes.

00:28:08.600 --> 00:28:12.580
Independently Richard Roberts, a
scientist at Cold Spring Harbor,

00:28:12.580 --> 00:28:17.300
and Phil Sharp, who had been at
Cold Spring Harbor but was now

00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:22.290
by this time at MIT, performed
essentially the same experiment.

00:28:22.290 --> 00:28:29.060 position:56%
They captured the messenger RNA from
a viral gene and then hybridized it

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:33.750
to the original DNA gene, and
when they did so and looked at it

00:28:33.750 --> 00:28:39.370
under the electron microscope
they found these loops, okay?

00:28:39.370 --> 00:28:46.430
So the messenger RNA, you can
see, is binding to the DNA

00:28:46.430 --> 00:28:51.040
and it's skipping over
chunks of the DNA.

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:55.540
In other words, the DNA
gene existed in segments

00:28:55.540 --> 00:28:58.010
with little spacers
in between them, okay?

00:28:58.010 --> 00:29:04.210 position:56%
This was one of the many discoveries
in science that made anomalies

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:08.200
in other researchers'
data suddenly make sense.

00:29:08.200 --> 00:29:12.430
Rich Roberts told me back in
1993 they all had the data

00:29:12.430 --> 00:29:16.870
in their notebooks, all they had to
do was go back and reinterpret it.

00:29:16.870 --> 00:29:19.460
Gilbert went back and
reinterpreted it.

00:29:19.460 --> 00:29:25.460
So after the symposium
he took a trip to Europe.

00:29:25.460 --> 00:29:29.590
Gilbert likes to travel the
world, and he went to Switzerland

00:29:29.590 --> 00:29:33.960
to visit Tonegawa, he went to
Poland to visit another scientist.

00:29:33.960 --> 00:29:40.330
And as he was traveling around
he said he had a big idea.

00:29:41.450 --> 00:29:45.230
The genes weren't in pieces,
he thought, they weren't just

00:29:45.230 --> 00:29:48.450
in pieces, he thought,
they must be modular.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:54.450
He imagined that the coding regions
represented ancient mini genes

00:29:54.450 --> 00:29:57.560
that would have functioned on
their own and he was already

00:29:57.560 --> 00:30:01.230
by this time calling the
intervening sequences introns

00:30:01.230 --> 00:30:04.120
and the coding regions exons, okay?

00:30:04.120 --> 00:30:07.530
And the evolutionary role
of introns, he thought,

00:30:07.530 --> 00:30:12.870
was to enable the exons
to be shuffled in order

00:30:12.870 --> 00:30:16.730
to rapidly create complex genes.

00:30:16.730 --> 00:30:20.060
When I came back to Harvard for
the fall term, Gilbert told me,

00:30:20.060 --> 00:30:23.600
I was very excited about the
exon shuffling idea and gave it

00:30:23.600 --> 00:30:26.170
as a seminar, centering
on the idea that genes

00:30:26.170 --> 00:30:29.090
and pieces might explain
the Cambrian evolution,

00:30:29.090 --> 00:30:30.390
Cambrian explosion.

00:30:30.390 --> 00:30:36.760
The evolutionary burst around 540
million years ago in which most

00:30:36.760 --> 00:30:40.020
of the major animal phyla appeared.

00:30:40.020 --> 00:30:44.040
Introns had not been seen in
bacteria, they'd only been seen

00:30:44.040 --> 00:30:45.520
in eukaryotes, higher organisms.

00:30:45.520 --> 00:30:51.340
So if, as many people believed,
simple prokaryotes, like bacteria,

00:30:51.340 --> 00:30:56.440
had evolved into complex
eukaryotes then Gilbert thought the

00:30:56.440 --> 00:31:00.740
introduction of introns could
have sped the diversification

00:31:00.740 --> 00:31:04.450
of higher organisms leading
to the Cambrian explosion.

00:31:04.450 --> 00:31:09.400
Now note that this reasoning is
based on a lot of assumptions

00:31:09.400 --> 00:31:12.090
that are no longer believed
as to be true, okay?

00:31:12.090 --> 00:31:13.390
But this is the way he was thinking

00:31:13.390 --> 00:31:17.200
and it was reasonable
thinking at the time.

00:31:17.200 --> 00:31:22.200
So Ford Doolittle began a
sabbatical year in Gilbert's lab

00:31:22.200 --> 00:31:26.410
that same fall, when Gilbert
came back all excited.

00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:31.300
And he remembers Gilbert's
seminar and he told me

00:31:31.300 --> 00:31:34.130
that afterward he went
home that night

00:31:34.130 --> 00:31:38.370
and wrote an essay in response.

00:31:38.370 --> 00:31:41.500
Doolittle had trained
under Carl Woese,

00:31:41.500 --> 00:31:46.370
who was at this time campaigning
heavily to get rid of this idea

00:31:46.370 --> 00:31:51.270
of a prokaryote to eukaryote
progression in evolution.

00:31:51.270 --> 00:31:56.980
And Doolittle was kind infected
with that idea, why should we think

00:31:56.980 --> 00:32:04.150
that prokaryotes were primitive
and disadvantaged, he reasoned,

00:32:04.150 --> 00:32:07.380
perhaps introns had always
been present all the way back

00:32:07.380 --> 00:32:12.420
to the last common ancestor and
had subsequently been streamlined

00:32:12.420 --> 00:32:18.200
out of the prokaryotic
lineage, enabling them to adapt

00:32:18.200 --> 00:32:20.090
in a different way
to their environment.

00:32:20.090 --> 00:32:26.050
So this became known as the
introns early theory, okay?

00:32:26.050 --> 00:32:29.120
Well, Gilbert liked this idea.

00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:32.450
It pushed exon shuffling
back earlier in evolution

00:32:32.450 --> 00:32:38.320
than he'd thought, so he had to
relinquish the Cambrian explosion,

00:32:38.320 --> 00:32:43.420
but shuffling and in return he
gained evolutionary primacy,

00:32:43.420 --> 00:32:46.860
this was a fundamental
thing in evolution.

00:32:46.860 --> 00:32:50.730
So that seemed a good tradeoff.

00:32:50.730 --> 00:32:57.610
And he wrote up this idea as a now
classic essay, why genes in pieces?

00:32:57.610 --> 00:33:00.740
This appeared in February of 1978

00:33:00.740 --> 00:33:05.100
and Ford Doolittle's response
appeared two months later in April.

00:33:05.100 --> 00:33:09.560
In a conference paper
titled Playgrounds

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:13.350
of Evolution published the
next year Gilbert argued

00:33:13.350 --> 00:33:18.040
that if exons were mini genes
then they ought to correspond

00:33:18.040 --> 00:33:21.720
to functional protein
domains, right?

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:24.980
They ought to have made
functional things at one point

00:33:24.980 --> 00:33:27.610
and if they were mixed and matched

00:33:27.610 --> 00:33:31.310
to put together more complex things
you ought to see them correspond

00:33:31.310 --> 00:33:33.910
when you look at more
complicated proteins,

00:33:33.910 --> 00:33:39.020
such as this immunoglobulin
molecule, okay?

00:33:39.020 --> 00:33:41.940
And so the pool of
exons and the genome

00:33:41.940 --> 00:33:45.950
at any given time would
provide a set of Lego-like parts

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:50.280
from which evolution could
draw to make complex proteins.

00:33:50.280 --> 00:33:54.270
He concluded poetically that exons
were inserted into a background

00:33:54.270 --> 00:33:58.900
of noncoding DNA, like bubbles
he wrote the exons float

00:33:58.900 --> 00:34:01.460
on a sea of introns.

00:34:01.460 --> 00:34:06.490
In 1980 Gilbert received a
Nobel Prize for DNA sequencing.

00:34:06.490 --> 00:34:10.290
In his Nobel lecture he
talked about DNA sequencing,

00:34:10.290 --> 00:34:11.590
but he also spent a lot

00:34:11.590 --> 00:34:15.040
of time discussing
evolution and exon shuffling.

00:34:15.040 --> 00:34:18.980
So clearly these ideas were
all linked in his mind.

00:34:20.110 --> 00:34:23.610
Well, Doolittle began
to diverge from Gilbert.

00:34:23.610 --> 00:34:28.340
Evolution, he said, can't think
ahead and invent things in order

00:34:28.340 --> 00:34:30.680
to speed future evolution, right?

00:34:30.680 --> 00:34:36.020
In 1980, jumping off from
Richard Dawkin's argument

00:34:36.020 --> 00:34:42.610
that an organism is a gene's way of
making more genes, Doolittle said

00:34:42.610 --> 00:34:46.360
in essence, wait a second,
not all DNA is genes,

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:50.700
any DNA that replicates
itself ought to spread whether

00:34:50.700 --> 00:34:52.890
or not it encodes a protein.

00:34:52.890 --> 00:34:56.530
This suggests that a lot of
DNA should merely be junk,

00:34:56.530 --> 00:35:00.550
and this is the origin of
the notion of junk DNA,

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:01.850
which you've probably heard.

00:35:01.850 --> 00:35:05.720
Francis Crick and Leslie Orgel
had roughly the same idea

00:35:05.720 --> 00:35:10.660
at the same time, selfish DNA they
said could be considered parasitic

00:35:10.660 --> 00:35:15.460
because it takes metabolic energy
to make and to maintain it,

00:35:15.460 --> 00:35:19.670
so it should have some cost
to the organism, right?

00:35:19.670 --> 00:35:24.310
And they published the ideas back
to back in the Journal Nature.

00:35:24.310 --> 00:35:31.180
It was on this background
- did I go forward, okay -

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:36.050
it was on this background then
that catalytic RNA was discovered.

00:35:36.050 --> 00:35:42.350
In 1982 working with the
eukaryotic pond animal tetrahymena,

00:35:42.350 --> 00:35:48.220
pictured here on the left, Tom
Cech at Colorado found an intron

00:35:48.220 --> 00:35:55.280 position:56%
in a ribosomal RNA gene that spliced
itself out of the messenger RNA.

00:35:55.280 --> 00:35:57.650
It didn't require another
enzyme to come in

00:35:57.650 --> 00:36:01.100
and cut it up, it could
just hop out.

00:36:01.100 --> 00:36:07.230
The next year Sid Altman at Yale
published a paper on RNase P,

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:12.440
which is an enzyme that has a
protein part and an RNA part,

00:36:12.440 --> 00:36:18.660 position:56%
and what it does is snip off part
of the transfer RNA and activate it.

00:36:18.660 --> 00:36:24.790
And accidentally in a control
experiment he found that one

00:36:24.790 --> 00:36:26.520
of his technicians actually found

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:31.800
that the RNA component alone
could catalyze that reaction,

00:36:31.800 --> 00:36:35.270
and so this was a big surprise.

00:36:35.270 --> 00:36:38.950
So we have two examples back
to back of catalytic RNA,

00:36:38.950 --> 00:36:41.170
now we know that this
can actually happen.

00:36:41.170 --> 00:36:47.390
So these papers caused a sensation
accompanied by much speculation.

00:36:48.430 --> 00:36:54.000
And so in 1985 Norm Pace, another
member of the Carl Woese age,

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:59.060
suggested that Cech's self-splicing
introns could be parasitic,

00:36:59.060 --> 00:37:03.080
selfish transposons,
ala Crick and Doolittle.

00:37:03.080 --> 00:37:05.200
He also proposed an RNA world.

00:37:05.200 --> 00:37:09.640
He suggested that originally RNA
could have served as both genotype

00:37:09.640 --> 00:37:12.610
and phenotype, in other words,
as both gene and enzyme.

00:37:12.610 --> 00:37:16.670
So this is an important idea
because it links this intron idea

00:37:16.670 --> 00:37:22.720
and selfish DNA to the idea of
RNA as the original molecule.

00:37:22.720 --> 00:37:24.400
But Gilbert stuck to his guns,

00:37:24.400 --> 00:37:27.910
the same year he revisited
his exon theory of genes,

00:37:27.910 --> 00:37:32.050
comparing it against the data
that had been gathered since 1978.

00:37:32.050 --> 00:37:38.500
In some cases the predictions
bore him out, in other cases not.

00:37:38.500 --> 00:37:41.870
Ever the optimist he concluded
that the glass was half full,

00:37:41.870 --> 00:37:46.500
the exon theory of genes, he
said, had held up rather well.

00:37:46.500 --> 00:37:51.270
This then is the context
for Gilbert's classic paper,

00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:55.250
which we can call The
RNA Only World.

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:59.620
He opened the paper with the
recent discoveries of RNA splicing,

00:37:59.620 --> 00:38:02.640
but they were several
years old by this time,

00:38:02.640 --> 00:38:05.190
why an editorial at this moment?

00:38:05.190 --> 00:38:07.750
Because the paper was
as much about introns

00:38:07.750 --> 00:38:10.970
as it was about RNA splicing.

00:38:10.970 --> 00:38:14.430
Most people quote the deservedly
famous line from the paper,

00:38:14.430 --> 00:38:20.440
one can contemplate an RNA world
containing only RNA molecules

00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:25.040
that serve to catalyze the
synthesis of themselves.

00:38:29.830 --> 00:38:35.640
And this then is the
classical RNA world described

00:38:35.640 --> 00:38:38.800
with Gilbert's characteristic
literary flare.

00:38:38.800 --> 00:38:43.290
But the paper also stated this
picture of the RNA world is one

00:38:43.290 --> 00:38:46.900
of replicating molecules
that re-assort exons

00:38:46.900 --> 00:38:52.350
by transposable elements
created by introns, okay?

00:38:52.350 --> 00:38:55.460
So in a recent e-mail
Gilbert confirmed,

00:38:55.460 --> 00:38:59.960
my stress in the RNA world
paper, he said, was twofold.

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:02.980
One was being struck with
the idea of RNA splicing,

00:39:02.980 --> 00:39:07.340
with the idea of RNA enzymes
doing everything, he said,

00:39:07.340 --> 00:39:12.230
and the second was the RNA based
exon shuffling of RNA pieces

00:39:12.230 --> 00:39:15.460
as a way of speeding up evolution.

00:39:15.460 --> 00:39:20.840 position:56%
But the second idea would be written
out of the received narrative.

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:25.860 position:56%
Gilbert's paper led to a Cold Spring
Harbor Symposium the next year

00:39:25.860 --> 00:39:30.050
in which one of our participants,
