01:05:45.880 --> 01:05:48.650
Using the natural physical
and chemical characteristics

01:05:48.650 --> 01:05:52.780
of environments, like hydrothermal
vent chimneys, as templates

01:05:52.780 --> 01:05:57.730
or analogs for some of
these reactions to occur.

01:05:57.730 --> 01:06:02.770
John Barose's group, with
the lead Author Eva Stueken,

01:06:02.770 --> 01:06:06.510
put out this really nice paper a
few years ago in geobiology sort

01:06:06.510 --> 01:06:09.940
of tying together not just at
the hydrothermal vent scale

01:06:09.940 --> 01:06:13.050
but at the global scale
how earth could serve

01:06:13.050 --> 01:06:16.600
as a global chemical reactor
providing different catalysts

01:06:16.600 --> 01:06:19.050
and different reaction
conditions as part

01:06:19.050 --> 01:06:22.230
of a dynamic system
encompassing many

01:06:22.230 --> 01:06:25.750
of the different inputs we've
talked about already - meteorites,

01:06:25.750 --> 01:06:28.770
atmospheric chemistry
and hydrothermalism.

01:06:28.770 --> 01:06:31.450
So the world is complex,
it's complex now,

01:06:31.450 --> 01:06:35.430
and it was complex back four
billion year ago, as well.

01:06:35.430 --> 01:06:39.070
And I think we need to take
this complexity and diversity

01:06:39.070 --> 01:06:43.050
into account rather than being
pigeonholed into a particular type

01:06:43.050 --> 01:06:48.830
of reaction or region
where it can occur.

01:06:48.830 --> 01:06:52.210
So, as I mentioned, the
ancient earth was complex,

01:06:52.210 --> 01:06:53.650
but so is the modern earth.

01:06:53.650 --> 01:06:57.850
This is an example of a
heavily serpentinized rock,

01:06:57.850 --> 01:06:59.570
a water rock reaction.

01:06:59.570 --> 01:07:02.890
The microbes, this is
a common sort of system

01:07:02.890 --> 01:07:07.270 position:56%
that my laboratory studies, one type
of system where water is flowing

01:07:07.270 --> 01:07:09.480
through subsurface materials.

01:07:09.480 --> 01:07:17.020
All this mosaic and mosaic fracture
network here are the habitats

01:07:17.020 --> 01:07:20.320
in which microorganisms
and these systems occur.

01:07:20.320 --> 01:07:27.890
But I'm not an organic chemist,
I'm not a paleontologist or any

01:07:27.890 --> 01:07:31.580
of these things, my laboratory
studies environmental biology.

01:07:31.580 --> 01:07:33.590
We get out in the field, we go

01:07:33.590 --> 01:07:35.640
to extreme environments
and we collect samples.

01:07:35.640 --> 01:07:38.220
We try to figure out how
the microbes are operating,

01:07:38.220 --> 01:07:41.170
how they survive these
conditions, how they interact

01:07:41.170 --> 01:07:44.510
with the geochemical and
physical environments.

01:07:44.510 --> 01:07:50.180 position:56%
And then if there are clues within
these systems that tell us something

01:07:50.180 --> 01:07:55.720
as analogs to earlier conditions,
you know, I think they can be used

01:07:55.720 --> 01:08:00.030
to inform some of these
bottom-up types of approaches.

01:08:00.030 --> 01:08:02.900
But the other thing that
I haven't heard mentioned

01:08:02.900 --> 01:08:06.640 position:56%
yet that I think is really valuable
about these types of environments is

01:08:06.640 --> 01:08:08.590
that these are systems
on the modern day earth

01:08:08.590 --> 01:08:12.610
where you have this interface
of abiotic and biotic processes.

01:08:12.610 --> 01:08:16.580
As you drill down deeper into
the earth you cross some divide

01:08:16.580 --> 01:08:18.430
or you're likely to
cross some divide.

01:08:18.430 --> 01:08:21.040
We haven't reached
it yet in some cases,

01:08:21.040 --> 01:08:26.360
between abiotic carbon cycling
and the biosphere, right?

01:08:26.360 --> 01:08:28.940
And we need to study
these systems carefully

01:08:28.940 --> 01:08:31.160
and understand how organisms

01:08:31.160 --> 01:08:34.680
in these systems might use
these abiotic compounds and how

01:08:34.680 --> 01:08:38.640
to define the properties of
living and nonliving systems.

01:08:38.640 --> 01:08:42.340
So the point is I think the
environments I'm going to describe

01:08:42.340 --> 01:08:47.220
in just a second here have
values not just as analogs

01:08:47.220 --> 01:08:52.680
for early earth type of conditions,
but also as observatories,

01:08:52.680 --> 01:08:57.500
places to look to better understand
the relationship between living

01:08:57.500 --> 01:08:59.740
and nonliving parts of the earth.

01:08:59.740 --> 01:09:01.570
So one of our favorite types

01:09:01.570 --> 01:09:04.340
of systems is the deep-sea
hydrothermal vents.

01:09:04.340 --> 01:09:06.980
Here's a typical example
of that here.

01:09:06.980 --> 01:09:10.200
These are places in the
middle of the ocean.

01:09:10.200 --> 01:09:14.890 position:56%
There's 65,000 kilometers along the
ocean ridge spreading center network

01:09:14.890 --> 01:09:19.820
on the planet right now
where seawater percolates

01:09:19.820 --> 01:09:22.860
through the subsurface, reacts
with the rock, and then is vented

01:09:22.860 --> 01:09:27.730
out through these hydrothermal vent
chimneys known as black smokers.

01:09:27.730 --> 01:09:31.510
Within the subsurface and within
the walls of these chimneys,

01:09:31.510 --> 01:09:35.990
which can be tens of
meters off of the sea floor,

01:09:35.990 --> 01:09:40.850
you have really steep gradients
in temperature and chemistry

01:09:40.850 --> 01:09:45.850
between the 300 plus degrees
Celsius hydrothermal fluids

01:09:45.850 --> 01:09:47.560
and the 2 degrees Celsius seawater.

01:09:47.560 --> 01:09:54.180
These fluids are also very diverse
in terms of their chemistry.

01:09:54.180 --> 01:09:57.780
The hydrothermal fluid
is full of metals,

01:09:57.780 --> 01:10:01.280
which make this the black smoke
that's coming out of the chimney,

01:10:01.280 --> 01:10:08.880
whereas, the seawater is largely
oxic and has a variety of compounds

01:10:08.880 --> 01:10:13.870
that can be used potentially
to oxidize or respire some

01:10:13.870 --> 01:10:18.830
of these components coming out
of the hydrothermal fluids.

01:10:18.830 --> 01:10:22.050
Just a few years ago or now it's
been more than a few years ago,

01:10:22.050 --> 01:10:23.740
but back in 2000 a new type

01:10:23.740 --> 01:10:27.570
of hydrothermal system was
discovered called the Lost City

01:10:27.570 --> 01:10:29.660
hydrothermal field.

01:10:29.660 --> 01:10:33.820
This was discovered near the
Mid-Atlantic Ridge by a group

01:10:33.820 --> 01:10:36.320
of researchers at the
University of Washington,

01:10:36.320 --> 01:10:39.420
and the differences
here are that instead

01:10:39.420 --> 01:10:42.350
of having very high temperature
hydrothermal fluids coming

01:10:42.350 --> 01:10:44.760
out that are very acidic
and metal rich,

01:10:44.760 --> 01:10:49.570
here you have fluids influenced by
a process called serpetinization,

01:10:49.570 --> 01:10:51.870
which are very high pH and rich,

01:10:51.870 --> 01:10:55.340
even higher concentrations
of methane and hydrogen.

01:10:55.340 --> 01:10:58.590
So these are a completely
different sort of chemistry

01:10:58.590 --> 01:11:04.440
than you typically see at the black
smoker type of magnetic systems.

01:11:04.440 --> 01:11:06.990
More moderate temperatures
in the sense,

01:11:06.990 --> 01:11:10.460
and typically where these
things occur are not places

01:11:10.460 --> 01:11:13.700
where magnetic activity
occurs, but these are associated

01:11:13.700 --> 01:11:20.490
with commonly tectonic activity,
earthquakes, that offset the plates

01:11:20.490 --> 01:11:23.520
from one another and
allow fluids to circulate.

01:11:23.520 --> 01:11:28.600
And then a third type of system we
work at are subaerial volcanoes.

01:11:28.600 --> 01:11:31.400
So, in particular, we
look at microbes that live

01:11:31.400 --> 01:11:34.110
within these volcanic
fumaroles and try

01:11:34.110 --> 01:11:37.020
to study how they're using
all this gas that's coming

01:11:37.020 --> 01:11:38.440
out of these fumaroles.

01:11:38.440 --> 01:11:42.260
These gases can include
hydrogen, sulfur compounds,

01:11:42.260 --> 01:11:44.910
things that you might
see in sketches

01:11:44.910 --> 01:11:47.480
of what the early earth
might look like.

01:11:47.480 --> 01:11:49.370
these things are occurring
right now in places

01:11:49.370 --> 01:11:52.830
like Komatke [Assumed Spelling] in
Siberia And the Aleutian Islands

01:11:52.830 --> 01:11:56.380
and all along the ring of
fire, really, in the Pacific.

01:11:56.380 --> 01:11:59.620
So here you have materials
that accumulates

01:11:59.620 --> 01:12:03.150
on the ocean floor then subducted
back into the earth and some

01:12:03.150 --> 01:12:06.960
of this sways back out through
these extreme environments found

01:12:06.960 --> 01:12:09.520
in subaerial volcanoes.

01:12:10.710 --> 01:12:13.810
So I just want to make a
couple points about our studies

01:12:13.810 --> 01:12:15.110
of these sorts of systems.

01:12:15.110 --> 01:12:19.590
The first of which is organisms
in these systems don't grow

01:12:19.590 --> 01:12:25.140
in your typical flask or beaker
full of material, they don't grow

01:12:25.140 --> 01:12:27.430
in a liquid phase commonly.

01:12:27.430 --> 01:12:29.820
These systems are dynamic systems.

01:12:29.820 --> 01:12:33.230
If Nathaniel showed you
some pictures of his trip

01:12:33.230 --> 01:12:37.460
to Yellowstone this summer he might
show you streamers and biofilms,

01:12:37.460 --> 01:12:39.880
slimy communities growing
in the outflow

01:12:39.880 --> 01:12:42.320
from the hydrothermal pools there.

01:12:42.320 --> 01:12:45.820
The organisms in these systems
want to stay attached to surfaces,

01:12:45.820 --> 01:12:50.530
they want to stay in
their happy place in terms

01:12:50.530 --> 01:12:52.590 position:56%
of these thermal-chemical gradients.

01:12:52.590 --> 01:12:56.760
And they grow attached to these
catalytic mineral surfaces,

01:12:56.760 --> 01:13:01.260
so many of the same surfaces
and minerals we evoke to serve

01:13:01.260 --> 01:13:05.530
as catalysts in our abiogenic
synthesis reactions are also the

01:13:05.530 --> 01:13:07.820
substrates for microbes to grow on.

01:13:07.820 --> 01:13:12.750
So here's an example of microbes
that grew on the surface of a piece

01:13:12.750 --> 01:13:15.230
of iron sulfide or pyrite mineral

01:13:15.230 --> 01:13:17.320
that we stuck in a
hydrothermal vent.

01:13:17.320 --> 01:13:21.550
You can see they form colonies,
they divide, they disperse,

01:13:21.550 --> 01:13:25.890
and they pattern themselves
all over this surface.

01:13:25.890 --> 01:13:31.260 position:56%
At the Lost City hydrothermal field
this serpetinization influenced high

01:13:31.260 --> 01:13:32.980
pH system.

01:13:32.980 --> 01:13:36.180
There's also interesting
insights from looking at biofilms.

01:13:36.180 --> 01:13:39.050
For example, when we go into
the hydrothermal chimneys

01:13:39.050 --> 01:13:45.140 position:56%
at the Lost City we see almost a
single species of biofilms comprised

01:13:45.140 --> 01:13:48.640
of archaea related to
methanogenic archaea

01:13:48.640 --> 01:13:50.810
within these hydrothermal
vent chimneys.

01:13:50.810 --> 01:13:56.000
The picture on the upper right
here shows some of the polymers,

01:13:56.000 --> 01:13:59.490
these polymeric matrix that
holds these cells together.

01:13:59.490 --> 01:14:00.910
In this sense it's dehydrated,

01:14:00.910 --> 01:14:03.520
but these organisms are
encapsulated together

01:14:03.520 --> 01:14:06.540
in a bed of slime, more or less.

01:14:06.540 --> 01:14:11.620
This biofilms are held
together and attached

01:14:11.620 --> 01:14:14.980
to the surfaces using polymers,
such as polysaccharides,

01:14:14.980 --> 01:14:17.460
which keep them in place.

01:14:17.460 --> 01:14:22.280
So the point of this is not only
do the organisms have some sort

01:14:22.280 --> 01:14:26.480
of very tightly coupled interaction
with the catalytic surfaces,

01:14:26.480 --> 01:14:29.770
but they grow as communities
in these polymers

01:14:29.770 --> 01:14:34.490 position:56%
and this polymeric matrix, this gel,
might serve some important roles

01:14:34.490 --> 01:14:38.590
in terms of thinking about how
different organosynthesis reactions

01:14:38.590 --> 01:14:42.830
may couple together to form
some of the first protocells.

01:14:43.930 --> 01:14:49.490 position:56%
They may also serve as templates for
minerals, especially nano particles

01:14:49.490 --> 01:14:55.870
and small scale minerals that may
also serve as catalysts to occur.

01:14:55.870 --> 01:14:58.620
So these charged biofilms,

01:14:58.620 --> 01:15:03.410
these gel-like matrices can
instigate the precipitation

01:15:03.410 --> 01:15:04.930
of small minerals.

01:15:04.930 --> 01:15:07.290
These minerals may serve
as more effective catalysts

01:15:07.290 --> 01:15:09.210
when dispersed throughout the film.

01:15:09.210 --> 01:15:14.350
So this is another part where even
the properties of the biofilm,

01:15:14.350 --> 01:15:17.040
itself, even if they aren't
cellular may serve a role

01:15:17.040 --> 01:15:21.450
in facilitating some of the
early prebiotic chemistry

01:15:21.450 --> 01:15:23.070
and organosynthesis reactions.

01:15:23.070 --> 01:15:27.540
So for one thing I would encourage
studying these small scale

01:15:27.540 --> 01:15:29.850
properties and the role
of biofilms and polymers

01:15:29.850 --> 01:15:32.790
in origins of life research.

01:15:32.790 --> 01:15:36.160
The second thing is it's
very attractive to think

01:15:36.160 --> 01:15:40.630
about using these metal
sulfide catalysts

01:15:40.630 --> 01:15:42.940
or these different
metallic catalysts

01:15:42.940 --> 01:15:45.490
to drive organosynthesis reactions.

01:15:45.490 --> 01:15:49.610
We can show that simple
reactions occur fairly readily,

01:15:49.610 --> 01:15:52.560
especially as you heat them to
higher temperatures and put them

01:15:52.560 --> 01:15:56.410
under pressure, such as the
carbonyl insertion reaction shown

01:15:56.410 --> 01:15:58.510
in the middle here.

01:15:58.510 --> 01:16:01.230
We can also go out to
hydrothermal systems,

01:16:01.230 --> 01:16:04.710
like the rainbow hydrothermal
field in the middle of the Atlantic

01:16:04.710 --> 01:16:08.400
which is a hybrid system
between the high temperature

01:16:08.400 --> 01:16:10.520
and the ultramafic
systems I've described

01:16:10.520 --> 01:16:14.300
and find many different organic
molecules in the fluids coming

01:16:14.300 --> 01:16:18.440
out of these, which have isotopic
signatures and chemical signatures

01:16:18.440 --> 01:16:21.510
to show that they are
not produced by biology.

01:16:21.510 --> 01:16:26.420
So we have both observational
experimental sense

01:16:26.420 --> 01:16:29.590
that abiotic organic
geochemistry is happening

01:16:29.590 --> 01:16:32.090
at modern day hydrothermal vents.

01:16:32.090 --> 01:16:37.700
And it's attractive to look
at those data and then compare

01:16:37.700 --> 01:16:40.590
that to biochemical
pathways that we know about.

01:16:40.590 --> 01:16:44.690
For example, the reductive acetyl
CoA pathway and begin to plug

01:16:44.690 --> 01:16:47.270
and play with the different
mineral catalysts and think

01:16:47.270 --> 01:16:51.900
about how the different steps may
be catalyzed through the reaction.

01:16:51.900 --> 01:16:53.990
But the reality of this and sort

01:16:53.990 --> 01:16:58.890
of building upon what I was
describing earlier about the divide

01:16:58.890 --> 01:17:02.970
between living and
nonliving systems are

01:17:02.970 --> 01:17:05.930
that the world is not that simple.

01:17:05.930 --> 01:17:08.340
There's overlapping carbon sources

01:17:08.340 --> 01:17:10.210
and properties in all
of these systems.

01:17:10.210 --> 01:17:12.800
What we've found through
studies of deep earth materials

01:17:12.800 --> 01:17:14.100
and of hydrothermal systems is

01:17:14.100 --> 01:17:19.120
that organisms don't always use the
simplest molecules to metabolize,

01:17:19.120 --> 01:17:22.920 position:56%
they don't always use the CO2 or the
hydrogen, sometimes they use some

01:17:22.920 --> 01:17:27.160
of these simple organic compounds
produced by abiotic processes,

01:17:27.160 --> 01:17:31.140 position:56%
sometimes they use the hydrocarbons,
the methane and other compounds.

01:17:31.140 --> 01:17:34.740
And so it's not always so
clear as to what's biotic

01:17:34.740 --> 01:17:36.420
and abiotic in these systems.

01:17:36.420 --> 01:17:38.180
Certainly interesting
to think about in terms

01:17:38.180 --> 01:17:40.860
of astrobiological
exploration, right?

01:17:40.860 --> 01:17:42.930
We'd like to know,
study these systems

01:17:42.930 --> 01:17:47.360
and understand what's evidence
of life and what's not.

01:17:47.360 --> 01:17:50.550
But as for exploring deeper parts

01:17:50.550 --> 01:17:56.270
of the earth's biosphere right
now it's sometimes difficult to go

01:17:56.270 --> 01:18:00.070
from a very simple
explanation like this

01:18:00.070 --> 01:18:03.020 position:56%
to the complexity of the real world.

01:18:03.020 --> 01:18:07.570 position:56%
So, again, I would encourage
studies of these analog type systems

01:18:07.570 --> 01:18:11.760
in order to help us better
define the properties of abiotic

01:18:11.760 --> 01:18:14.790
and biological carbon
compounds in these systems.

01:18:14.790 --> 01:18:17.420
And then we haven't even gotten
into the fact that we're covered

01:18:17.420 --> 01:18:20.270
with life on the surface and
that complicates everything,

01:18:20.270 --> 01:18:21.930
it eats a lot of carbon
that's produced

01:18:21.930 --> 01:18:27.310 position:56%
and just makes it a big mess, right?

01:18:27.310 --> 01:18:32.690
And then, thirdly, I want to talk
about we've had this in biology,

01:18:32.690 --> 01:18:37.530
we've had this genomics revolution
over the past 20 years or so,

01:18:37.530 --> 01:18:44.030
where nowadays we don't have to
deal with radioactive phosphorous

01:18:44.030 --> 01:18:46.930
in terms of our sequencing,
like Maxam and Gilbert

01:18:46.930 --> 01:18:49.090
and Sanger did in those days.

01:18:49.090 --> 01:18:52.290
Nowadays we can just send
samples off on a plate

01:18:52.290 --> 01:18:56.740
and have results overnight
or in very short order.

01:18:56.740 --> 01:19:01.940
Many orders of magnitude, more
at DNA sequences than we used to.

01:19:01.940 --> 01:19:05.810
Nowadays we're drowning
in data in many cases.

01:19:05.810 --> 01:19:10.720
So this has really enabled us to
look at biology in a whole new way.

01:19:10.720 --> 01:19:14.020
So an example of this
the really exciting paper

01:19:14.020 --> 01:19:15.630
that was published just this summer

01:19:15.630 --> 01:19:17.660
by Bill Martin's group
over in Germany.

01:19:17.660 --> 01:19:21.300
Many of you have probably seen
something like this tree of life

01:19:21.300 --> 01:19:25.420
in the upper right here, thinking
about the lineages of bacteria

01:19:25.420 --> 01:19:29.750
and eukarya and archaea and how
they might have some last universal

01:19:29.750 --> 01:19:32.790 position:56%
common ancestry may have been shared
amongst these different lineages

01:19:32.790 --> 01:19:37.400
and thinking about what that
last common ancestor was

01:19:37.400 --> 01:19:38.700
and where it originated.

01:19:38.700 --> 01:19:42.960
Many of these trees traditionally
have been built upon just a few

01:19:42.960 --> 01:19:48.360
genes, primarily the small subunit
ribosomal RNA gene or 16S gene

01:19:48.360 --> 01:19:50.060
that you may have heard about.

01:19:50.060 --> 01:19:53.210
But this genomics revolution
I talked about has enabled us

01:19:53.210 --> 01:19:57.350
to look not just at individual
genes, but across whole genomes

01:19:57.350 --> 01:20:02.260
or bacterial chromosomes
to look at the properties

01:20:02.260 --> 01:20:06.850
of not just the ribosomal RNA
gene but any sort of function

01:20:06.850 --> 01:20:08.830
of phenotype that we
have some knowledge of.

01:20:08.830 --> 01:20:14.650
So Martin's group looked at over
2,000 different prokaryotic genomes

01:20:14.650 --> 01:20:17.070
from the sequencing
analyses and boiled it

01:20:17.070 --> 01:20:19.950
down to 355 protein families

01:20:19.950 --> 01:20:23.890
that were shared amongst multiple
lineages across the tree of life.

01:20:23.890 --> 01:20:28.140
And what they found out was
that they found some clues

01:20:28.140 --> 01:20:32.280
to the metabolic and
physiological properties of some

01:20:32.280 --> 01:20:35.840
that were likely shared by the
last universal common ancestor

01:20:35.840 --> 01:20:40.520 position:56%
and that leuka was probably an
anaerobic thermophile likely related

01:20:40.520 --> 01:20:42.940
to cluster of the LEs [Assumed
Spelling] or methanogens

01:20:42.940 --> 01:20:46.150
and that things like
hydrogen, nitrogen

01:20:46.150 --> 01:20:50.030
and carbon monoxide were all
important in its metabolism.

01:20:50.030 --> 01:20:51.550
So some of these things
sound familiar

01:20:51.550 --> 01:20:52.900
with what we've already described,

01:20:52.900 --> 01:20:55.440
places like the Lost
City hydrothermal field

01:20:55.440 --> 01:21:00.630
or deep-sea vents, so it's very
encouraging that these sort

01:21:00.630 --> 01:21:03.060
of data were able to fall
out of this very complicated

01:21:03.060 --> 01:21:06.840
and thorough analyses
that they conducted.

01:21:06.840 --> 01:21:14.040
And but what Martin's group worked
